{
  "Which group on the periodic table contains the halogens?": "",
  "Group 1": "",
  "Group 17": "",
  "Group 18": "",
  "Group 2": "",
  "Halogens are found in Group 17 of the periodic table. They include fluorine, chlorine, bromine, iodine, and astatine.": "",
  "How many valence electrons do halogens have?": "",
  "1 valence electron": "",
  "8 valence electrons": "",
  "7 valence electrons": "",
  "2 valence electrons": "",
  "Halogens have 7 valence electrons. They need just 1 more electron to fill their outer shell, which makes them very reactive as they readily gain that extra electron.": "",
  "Which group on the periodic table contains the noble gases?": "",
  "Noble gases are in Group 18, the last column of the periodic table. They include helium, neon, argon, krypton, xenon, and radon.": "",
  "Why are noble gases considered unreactive?": "",
  "They have a full outer electron shell and are very stable": "",
  "They are too small to interact with other atoms at all": "",
  "They have no electrons in any of their energy levels": "",
  "They exist only at extremely high temperature conditions": "",
  "Noble gases have full outer electron shells (8 valence electrons, except helium with 2). This stable configuration means they have little tendency to gain, lose, or share electrons.": "",
  "In what physical states do halogens exist at room temperature?": "",
  "All halogens are solids at room temperature": "",
  "All halogens are gases at room temperature": "",
  "They exist as gases, liquids, and solids depending on the element": "",
  "All halogens are liquids at room temperature": "",
  "Halogens exist in all three states at room temperature: fluorine and chlorine are gases, bromine is a liquid, and iodine and astatine are solids.": "",
  "What charge do halogen ions typically form?": "",
  "+1 charge": "",
  "+2 charge": "",
  "-1 charge": "",
  "-2 charge": "",
  "Halogens form -1 ions by gaining one electron to fill their outer shell. For example, chlorine (Cl) gains one electron to become chloride (Cl-).": "",
  "Which halogen is used to disinfect drinking water and swimming pools?": "",
  "Fluorine": "",
  "Bromine": "",
  "Iodine": "",
  "Chlorine": "",
  "Chlorine is widely used to disinfect drinking water and swimming pools because it effectively kills harmful bacteria and other microorganisms.": "",
  "Which noble gas is used in colorful light-up signs?": "",
  "Helium": "",
  "Argon": "",
  "Neon": "",
  "Radon": "",
  "Neon produces a bright red-orange glow when electricity passes through it in a sealed tube. Other noble gases produce different colors and are also used in illuminated signs.": "",
  "As you go down Group 17 from fluorine to astatine, what happens to the reactivity of halogens?": "",
  "Reactivity increases going down the group": "",
  "Reactivity decreases going down the group": "",
  "Reactivity stays exactly the same throughout": "",
  "Reactivity alternates between high and low values": "",
  "Halogen reactivity decreases going down the group because larger atoms are less effective at attracting an additional electron. Fluorine is the most reactive halogen, and astatine is the least reactive.": "",
  "Which noble gas is lighter than air and commonly used to fill balloons?": "",
  "Krypton": "",
  "Helium is much lighter (less dense) than air, which is why helium-filled balloons float. Unlike hydrogen, helium is safe because it is nonflammable and completely unreactive.": "",
  "What is a halogen?": "",
  "A highly reactive nonmetal in Group 17 with 7 valence electrons": "",
  "An unreactive gas in Group 18 with a full outer electron shell": "",
  "A reactive metal in Group 1 that has only 1 valence electron": "",
  "A metalloid found along the staircase line of the periodic table": "",
  "A halogen is a highly reactive nonmetal element in Group 17 with 7 valence electrons. The name 'halogen' means 'salt-former' because they readily react with metals to form salts.": "",
  "What is a noble gas?": "",
  "A highly reactive gas that readily forms compounds with metals": "",
  "An extremely unreactive gas in Group 18 with a full outer shell": "",
  "A toxic gas found only in Group 17 of the periodic table today": "",
  "A heavy gas that sinks to the ground level in all environments": "",
  "A noble gas is an extremely unreactive gaseous element in Group 18 with a complete outer electron shell. They are sometimes called inert gases because of their very low reactivity.": "",
  "What does 'diatomic molecule' mean?": "",
  "A molecule made up of exactly two atoms bonded together as a pair": "",
  "A molecule that contains two different elements in its structure": "",
  "An atom that has exactly two electrons in its outermost shell": "",
  "A compound that can exist in exactly two states of matter only": "",
  "A diatomic molecule consists of exactly two atoms bonded together. Halogens naturally exist as diatomic molecules (F2, Cl2, Br2, I2) because each atom shares one electron with another to fill its outer shell.": "",
  "What does 'inert' mean when describing noble gases?": "",
  "Not chemically reactive under normal conditions of temperature and pressure": "",
  "Extremely reactive and dangerous when exposed to air or water at any time": "",
  "Heavy enough to sink in any liquid regardless of the liquid's own density": "",
  "Unable to exist as a gas and must always be stored as a solid or a liquid": "",
  "Inert means chemically nonreactive. Noble gases are called inert because their full outer electron shell makes them extremely stable, with little tendency to form chemical bonds.": "",
  "What is an anion?": "",
  "A negatively charged ion formed when an atom gains electrons": "",
  "A positively charged ion formed when an atom loses electrons": "",
  "A neutral atom that has not gained or lost any electrons yet": "",
  "A proton that has been removed from the nucleus of any atom": "",
  "An anion is a negatively charged ion formed when an atom gains one or more electrons. Halogens commonly form anions by gaining 1 electron, such as Cl- (chloride) and F- (fluoride).": "",
  "What does 'salt-former' mean in relation to halogens?": "",
  "Halogens react with metals to produce ionic compounds called salts": "",
  "Halogens are found naturally dissolved in the salt water of oceans": "",
  "Halogens taste salty when they are placed directly onto the tongue": "",
  "Halogens can convert table salt back into sodium and chlorine gas": "",
  "The word 'halogen' comes from Greek words meaning 'salt-former.' Halogens react with metals to form salts. Sodium chloride (table salt) is formed from sodium and the halogen chlorine.": "",
  "What does 'monatomic' mean when describing noble gases?": "",
  "They exist as single individual atoms rather than bonding in molecules": "",
  "They exist as pairs of atoms bonded together in diatomic molecules": "",
  "They can only exist in one physical state regardless of temperature": "",
  "They contain only one proton in the nucleus of their atoms each": "",
  "Monatomic means existing as single atoms. Unlike most nonmetals that bond to form molecules (like O2 or N2), noble gases exist as individual, unbonded atoms because their full outer shells make bonding unnecessary.": "",
  "What does 'electronegativity' mean for halogens?": "",
  "The tendency of an atom to attract electrons toward itself in a bond": "",
  "The tendency of an atom to release electrons from its outer shell": "",
  "The number of protons found inside the nucleus of a halogen atom": "",
  "The total energy needed to remove a halogen from a chemical bond": "",
  "Electronegativity is the ability of an atom to attract electrons in a chemical bond. Halogens have very high electronegativity because they strongly attract the one extra electron needed to fill their outer shell.": "",
  "What is a halide?": "",
  "A compound or ion formed when a halogen gains an electron and becomes negative": "",
  "A neutral halogen atom that has not yet participated in any chemical reaction": "",
  "A pair of halogen atoms bonded together forming a diatomic molecule in gas form": "",
  "A noble gas that shares similar chemical properties with the halogen elements": "",
  "A halide is the negative ion formed when a halogen atom gains one electron. Examples include fluoride (F-), chloride (Cl-), bromide (Br-), and iodide (I-).": "",
  "What does 'full outer shell' mean for noble gases?": "",
  "The outermost energy level contains the maximum number of electrons possible": "",
  "The noble gas atom has completely lost all electrons from every energy level": "",
  "Every energy level in the atom contains the same exact number of electrons": "",
  "The atom has more electrons than protons giving it a strong negative charge": "",
  "A full outer shell means the outermost energy level holds the maximum number of electrons it can (8 for most noble gases, 2 for helium). This makes noble gases very stable and unreactive.": "",
  "Fluorine is the most reactive of all the halogens. Why is it more reactive than chlorine, which is just below it in Group 17?": "",
  "Fluorine has more valence electrons than chlorine does overall": "",
  "Fluorine is smaller so its nucleus attracts electrons more strongly": "",
  "Fluorine has fewer protons which makes it react more vigorously": "",
  "Fluorine is a gas while chlorine is a liquid at room temperature": "",
  "Fluorine is smaller than chlorine with fewer electron shells, so its nucleus more strongly attracts incoming electrons. This stronger pull makes fluorine more effective at gaining the electron it needs.": "",
  "Helium is used in blimps and party balloons instead of hydrogen. Why is helium preferred even though hydrogen is lighter?": "",
  "Helium is easier to produce in large quantities than hydrogen is": "",
  "Helium is nonflammable and safe because it is an unreactive noble gas": "",
  "Helium produces more lift than hydrogen does in balloons and blimps": "",
  "Helium is heavier than air while hydrogen is lighter than air overall": "",
  "Helium is preferred because it is a noble gas and completely nonflammable. Hydrogen is dangerously flammable, as demonstrated by the Hindenburg disaster in 1937.": "",
  "A student notes that fluorine (F) and chlorine (Cl) are both gases, bromine (Br) is a liquid, and iodine (I) is a solid at room temperature. What trend explains this?": "",
  "Lighter halogens are more reactive so they stay as gases at room temp": "",
  "Boiling points increase down the group as atoms get larger and heavier": "",
  "Physical state is random and has no relationship to position in group": "",
  "The color of the halogen determines what physical state it will be in": "",
  "As you go down Group 17, atoms become larger with more electrons, leading to stronger intermolecular forces. This means higher boiling and melting points, changing the state from gas to liquid to solid.": "",
  "Argon gas is used inside incandescent light bulbs. Why would an unreactive noble gas be useful inside a light bulb?": "",
  "Argon helps the filament burn brighter by providing extra oxygen gas": "",
  "Argon prevents the hot filament from reacting with oxygen and burning out": "",
  "Argon conducts electricity better than a vacuum does inside the bulb": "",
  "Argon produces light on its own without needing any electrical current": "",
  "Argon's unreactivity protects the hot tungsten filament inside a light bulb. If oxygen were present, the filament would quickly oxidize (burn out). The inert argon prevents this reaction.": "",
  "Fluoride is added to toothpaste and drinking water to prevent tooth decay. Fluoride is the ion form of which halogen?": "",
  "Chlorine, the halogen used to disinfect water": "",
  "Bromine, the halogen that is a liquid at room temp": "",
  "Fluorine, the most reactive halogen in the group": "",
  "Iodine, the halogen that is a solid at room temp": "",
  "Fluoride (F-) is the ion of fluorine. When fluorine gains one electron, it becomes the fluoride ion. In toothpaste and water, fluoride helps strengthen tooth enamel and prevent cavities.": "",
  "A scientist wants to prevent a highly reactive metal from corroding. She places it in a sealed container filled with argon gas. Why would this help?": "",
  "Argon reacts with the metal to form a protective coating on its surface": "",
  "Argon is unreactive and will not react with the metal like oxygen would": "",
  "Argon freezes the metal which prevents any chemical reactions from occurring": "",
  "Argon absorbs all the moisture in the container preventing rust from forming": "",
  "Argon is an inert noble gas that does not react with anything under normal conditions. Replacing air (which contains reactive oxygen and moisture) with argon prevents the metal from corroding.": "",
  "Chlorine gas (Cl2) is toxic and was used as a weapon in World War I. However, chloride ions (Cl-) in table salt are safe to eat. How can the same element be both dangerous and safe?": "",
  "Chlorine gas and chloride ions are actually two completely different elements": "",
